You are debugging a production issue where a microservice fails to roll back database changes when a downstream logging operation fails. Despite the outer method catching the inner method's exception, the application throws an unexpected exception at the end of the transaction boundary. Here is the simplified class setup:

java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    @Autowired
    private OrderService self; // Self-injected to trigger proxy behavior
    @Autowired
    private AuditService auditService;

    @Transactional
    public void checkout(Order order) {
        try {
            saveOrder(order);
            auditService.logTransaction(order); // Throws RuntimeException
        } catch (RuntimeException e) {
            // Suppressing exception, intending to keep saveOrder transaction committed
            log.warn("Logging failed, but preserving transaction state", e);
        }
    }
}

@Service
public class AuditService {
    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRED)
    public void logTransaction(Order order) {
        throw new RuntimeException("Audit DB connection failure");
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput API gateway experiences severe thread starvation. The gateway aggregates responses from downstream legacy microservices using `CompletableFuture` combined with `.orTimeout()`. Under heavy network latency, threads are not returning to the pool even when timeouts are triggered successfully and fallback responses are returned to the client.

java
public CompletableFuture<Response> fetchWithTimeout() {
    return CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
        // Calls a legacy synchronous HTTP client
        return legacyHttpClient.executeGet("http://downstream/api/resource");
    }, customThreadPool)
    .orTimeout(500, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS)
    .exceptionally(ex -> {
        log.error("Timeout occurred, returning fallback", ex);
        return Response.FALLBACK;
    });
}

You are debugging a production issue in a distributed system where a payment microservice occasionally processes duplicate payments during periods of high database load and failovers. The service uses a distributed Redis lock to ensure idempotency. The implementation details are as follows:

java
public void processPayment(PaymentRequest request) {
    String lockKey = "lock:payment:" + request.getId();
    // Attempt to acquire lock with 5-second TTL
    if (redisLock.acquire(lockKey, 5, TimeUnit.SECONDS)) {
        try {
            paymentDatabaseService.executeTransaction(request);
        } finally {
            redisLock.release(lockKey);
        } 
    } else {
        throw new IdempotencyException("Request already in progress");
    }
}
